<div class="callout">
 <div class="callout-label">In-Gulf vessels vs. forward supply chains</div>
 <div class="callout-body">Two distinct risks require different analytical treatment. <strong>For vessels already inside the Persian Gulf — loaded, at berth, or at anchor awaiting loading — there is no alternative exit.</strong> The Strait is the only way out. Every such vessel, regardless of cargo type, faces binary exposure: it transits Hormuz, or it waits. This is the accumulation number for underwriters pricing in-window fleet exposure.

The second question is forward-looking: can an importer substitute supply over a longer horizon? For crude, the answer is yes — at a cost. West African, Brazilian, and North Sea crude can be sourced and routed via Cape at a voyage premium of approximately $3.5M per VLCC at current market rates. That option is painful but real. For LNG, no equivalent alternative supply exists. Qatari LNG cannot be replaced at scale from any other origin. <strong>Every LNG cargo in the Gulf is binary on both timeframes. Crude is binary for in-place vessels; it has a costly alternative for future supply.</strong> The reroute column in the table above reflects supply-chain optionality — not in-place vessel diversion.</div>
</div>

